ubbard.com%2Fwordpress%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2022%2F03%2Fstrcture-diagram.png&a=w%3D512%26h%3D288%26fm%3Dpng%26q%3D90&cd=2022-03-11T14%3A24%3A07 512w,/_gatsby/image/e2a7520630c77bebe684859806543653/64964b81e986135b3cff7281e39fc22b/strcture-diagram.png?u=https%3A%2F%2Flucashubbard.com%2Fwordpress%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2022%2F03%2Fstrcture-diagram.png&a=w%3D1024%26h%3D576%26fm%3Dpng%26q%3D90&cd=2022-03-11T14%3A24%3A07 1024w\",\"sizes\":\"(min-width: 1024px) 1024px, 100vw\"}},\"layout\":\"constrained\",\"width\":1024,\"height\":576},\"alt\":\"\",\"className\":\"wp-image-2793 inline-gatsby-image-wrapper\",\"data-wp-inline-image\":\"2\"}</script><figcaption>Diagram showing how the layout component functions</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<h2>Organizing My Style Sheet</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>CSS style sheets are notorious for being difficult to maintain. I wanted to make sure my style sheet would make sense to me when I come back to it months from now. I achieved this by separating my styles into logical sections using comment headings. The top of the document has rules for resetting default styles and color variables. Styles unique to one page sit under a comment header identifying the page they belong to. Sections are loosely laid out based on where they appear on the page. For example, the footer rules are at the bottom of the document just above the media queries.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Using WordPress as a Headless CMS</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Because I already had blog posts hosted on a WordPress site, I was eager to dynamically pull posts from my existing blog to my new blog. I was able to do this using GraphQL and the WordPress API. The front end (the head) is built with Gatsby while the back end data is stored in WordPress. This makes WordPress a headless content management system. I’m able to use all of the editing tools native to WordPress while still taking advantage of Gatsby&#8217;s speed, security, and enjoyable development experience. It took some fiddling to get the formatting and page routing right, but the final result is an attractive and maintainable blog.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>The Jam Session Player</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Jam sessions were a series of acoustic live performances I recorded between 2015 and 2017.  I wanted to create a custom playlist with a list of videos on the bottom and a video player at the top. I created an array of objects to store information on each video. Each object contains the video title, Youtube ID, and a boolean to denote visibility. I then loop over the array and display the video using React Player. If the visibility property is set to false, the CSS display property is set to none. Below the video player, I display a list of video thumbnails pulled from ytimg API using the Youtube ID. When a user clicks on a thumbnail, the corresponding video&#8217;s visibility is set to true and all other video&#8217;s visibility is set to false.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><div data-gatsby-image-wrapper=\"\" style=\"position:relative;overflow:hidden;display:inline-block;vertical-align:top\" class=\"gatsby-image-wrapper gatsby-image-wrapper-constrained wp-image-2805 inline-gatsby-image-wrapper\" data-reactroot=\"\"><div style=\"max-width:1024px;display:block\"><img alt=\"\" role=\"presentation\" aria-hidden=\"true\" src=\"data:image/svg+xml;charset=utf-8,%3Csvg height=&#x27;725&#x27; width=&#x27;1024&#x27; xmlns=&#x27;http://www.w3.org/2000/svg&#x27; version=&#x27;1.1&#x27;%3E%3C/svg%3E\" style=\"max-width:100%;display:block;position:static\"/></div><div aria-hidden=\"true\" data-placeholder-image=\"\" style=\"height:100%;left:0;position:absolute;top:0;width:100%\"></div><img data-gatsby-image-ssr=\"\" data-wp-inline-image=\"3\" data-main-image=\"\" style=\"height:100%;left:0;position:absolute;top:0;transform:translateZ(0);transition:opacity 250ms linear;width:100%;will-change:opacity;opacity:0\" sizes=\"(min-width: 1024px) 1024px, 100vw\" decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" data-src=\"/_gatsby/image/50b7